Its not so hard actually, tennis was way bigger in the 80s and maybe even 70s due to Graf and Becker.
The sport has a bad image I think of being a rich mans sport, which is partially true.
We have basically no public courts and while not as expensive as some people think its probably still the most expensive big sport.
We have no tennis academies like we do for football and you should never underestimate the value that is placed on education, lack of discipline and not believing in dreams.
There is a reason that many athletes here are immigrants. German parents often wont allow their kids to focus on sport instead of school and you bet your ass that Alexander Zverev made his sons train even if they didnt want to.
But the biggest reason is definitely the club culture and financial aspect, though I do think its getting better.
I feel like there are quite many active players in the age group 40-80, very few from 16-40 but then from 6-16 the number is relatively high again.
But maybe that just means that many teenagers quit and only come back when they have kids of their own for example

So in places like Spain, the UK, France and Italy they'll start a new season each year, knowing full well that one of three usual candidates will win the league, while smaller, less affluent teams will rot in the mid table or struggle to stay in the division.

Old local supporters will be forced to pay tickets that will get more pricey, thanks to national and international glory hunters.

After each season is over, every single year these teams will now be eligible to participate in one of two international European competitions, so that European fans can find out which were the best teams of the continent. The sign is a subtle joke. The shop is called "Sneed's Feed & Seed", where "feed" and "seed" both end in the sound "-eed", thus rhyming with the name of the owner, Sneed. The sign says that the shop was "Formerly Chuck's", implying that the two words beginning with "F" and "S" would have ended with "-uck", rhyming with "Chuck". So, when Chuck owned the shop, it would have been called "Chuck's Feeduck and Seeduck".

posts.com:
>>128364366
>Maybe with the 6 tournaments and the stat-padding that permits, 10 tournaments is too low for dai-yokozuna discussion ... There's only 18 total yokozuna with 10+ championships
Daiyokozuna doesn't mean 10 yusho. That's some weird Anglosphere concept; the Japanese do not reference it.
Daiyokozuna has historically been used to mean any yokozuna who was/is considered great, irrespective of anything else - for example, Tanikaze is considered a daiyokozuna despite the concept of 'winning' a basho not existing in his time.

The 10-yusho thing also ignores the historically evolving purpose of the yokozuna, which in its early days often was used to celebrate an ozeki who had been very good for a long time (who the House of Yoshida Tsukasa liked). If we count exclusively yusho following yokozuna promotion, Tanikaze had 3. If we count all career yusho, he had 21. Doing this leads to bizarre interpretations, like saying that the greatest yokozuna of all time by career win%, Umegatani I, can't be a daiyokozuna because he had 0 yusho at yokozuna.
